
🚀 Step 0: Prerequisites
You need:
EKS cluster running
kubectl configured
Access to cluster
Check:
kubectl get nodes
If you see nodes → good to go ✅

🔧 Step 1: Install EBS CSI Driver (IMPORTANT)
Without this, PVC will NOT work.
Run:
aws eks create-addon \
 --cluster-name <your-cluster-name> \
 --addon-name aws-ebs-csi-driver
Verify:
kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep ebs
You should see running pods.

📦 Step 2: Create StorageClass
This tells Kubernetes: “use AWS EBS gp3 disk”.
Create a file:
apiVersion: storage.k8s.io/v1
kind: StorageClass
metadata:
 name: gp3
provisioner: ebs.csi.aws.com
volumeBindingMode: WaitForFirstConsumer
parameters:
 type: gp3
Apply it:
kubectl apply -f storageclass.yaml
Check:
kubectl get sc

📄 Step 3: Create PVC (your storage request)
Create file:
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
 name: my-pvc
spec:
 accessModes:
   - ReadWriteOnce
 storageClassName: gp3
 resources:
   requests:
     storage: 5Gi
Apply:
kubectl apply -f pvc.yaml
Check:
kubectl get pvc
👉 At this point, it may show:
STATUS: Pending
That’s normal (don’t panic)

🚀 Step 4: Create Pod that uses PVC
Now we attach storage to a pod.
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
 name: my-app
spec:
 containers:
 - name: nginx
   image: nginx
   volumeMounts:
   - mountPath: "/data"
     name: my-storage
 volumes:
 - name: my-storage
   persistentVolumeClaim:
     claimName: my-pvc
Apply:
kubectl apply -f pod.yaml

✅ Step 5: Verify everything
Check pod:
kubectl get pods
Check PVC:
kubectl get pvc
Now it should say:
STATUS: Bound
🎉 That means:
PVC created
EBS volume created
Pod attached to disk

🔍 Step 6: Test storage
Enter pod:
kubectl exec -it my-app -- /bin/bash
Write file:
echo "hello from EKS" > /data/test.txt
cat /data/test.txt
If it works → storage is working ✅

⚠️ Common beginner mistakes (very important)
❌ PVC stuck in Pending forever
CSI driver not installed
Wrong StorageClass name

❌ Pod stuck in Pending
Node/AZ mismatch
Not enough resources

❌ Volume not shared
EBS supports only:

 ReadWriteOnce


If you need multiple pods → use Amazon EFS


Great—let’s level this up in a way that actually sticks. I’ll show you:
How to clean up everything safely
How to use shared storage (EFS)
A clear mental diagram so you understand what’s happening under the hood

🧹 1. Delete Everything (Clean Up)
When you’re done testing, delete in this order:
kubectl delete pod my-app
kubectl delete pvc my-pvc
kubectl delete sc gp3
⚠️ Important:
Deleting PVC → deletes the EBS volume automatically (if reclaim policy = Delete)
If not → you may need to manually delete from AWS console
Storage comes from Amazon EBS, so always clean up to avoid charges.

📂 2. Shared Storage (Multiple Pods) using EFS
EBS = one pod at a time
 EFS = many pods at the same time
We use Amazon EFS

🔧 Step 1: Create EFS in AWS
In AWS Console:
Go to EFS
Create file system
Select same VPC as EKS

🔧 Step 2: Install EFS CSI Driver
helm repo add aws-efs-csi-driver https://kubernetes-sigs.github.io/aws-efs-csi-driver
helm install aws-efs-csi-driver aws-efs-csi-driver/aws-efs-csi-driver \
 -n kube-system

📦 Step 3: Create StorageClass (EFS)
apiVersion: storage.k8s.io/v1
kind: StorageClass
metadata:
 name: efs-sc
provisioner: efs.csi.aws.com
Apply:
kubectl apply -f efs-sc.yaml

📄 Step 4: Create PVC (EFS)
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
 name: efs-pvc
spec:
 accessModes:
   - ReadWriteMany   # 👈 important
 storageClassName: efs-sc
 resources:
   requests:
     storage: 5Gi

🚀 Step 5: Use in Multiple Pods
You can attach same PVC to multiple pods:
volumeMounts:
 - mountPath: "/shared"
   name: shared-storage
Now all pods share same files 🎉

🧠 3. Architecture (Simple Visualization)
Here’s what actually happens:
[ Pod ]
  ↓
[ PVC ]  ← your request (5Gi)
  ↓
[ StorageClass ]
  ↓
[ CSI Driver ]
  ↓
[ AWS Storage ]
  → EBS (single pod)
  → EFS (multiple pods)

🔥 Real-World Tips (this is what people miss)
✅ Always use:
volumeBindingMode: WaitForFirstConsumer
Prevents AZ issues in EKS

✅ Use EBS for:
Databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL)
Single pod apps

✅ Use EFS for:
Shared logs
Multiple replicas
Microservices sharing data

❌ Avoid this mistake:
Trying:
ReadWriteMany with EBS
👉 Won’t work

